$:{TITLE("Google Drive Embedding", "Help", "/help")}

<div class="content">
  <div class="constrained">
    <h3>How do I find the embed link?</h3>

    <h4>For documents</h4>

    <p>
      In the <em>File</em> menu of your document, there is a <em>Publish to the web…</em> option.
    </p>

    <figure class="help-image">
      <img src="${resource_path('img/help/help-gdocs-1.png')}" width="276" height="334">
    </figure>

    <p>
      In this section, select <em>Start publishing</em>.
    </p>

    <figure class="help-image">
      <img src="${resource_path('img/help/help-gdocs-2.png')}" width="346" height="150">
    </figure>

    <p>
      The embed link is located inside the <em>Embed code</em> block of
      HTML. Pasting just the link is not necessary; Weasyl will take the link
      out of the whole embed code.
    </p>

    <figure class="help-image">
      <img src="${resource_path('img/help/help-gdocs-3.png')}" width="516" height="182">
    </figure>

    <h4>For anything else</h4>

    <p>
      Instead of a <em>Publish to the web…</em> option, PDFs will have
      an <em>Embed this PDF file…</em> option. Anything else will have
      an <em>Embed link…</em> option. The block of HTML in the
      resulting dialog contains the embed link. As with documents, pasting just
      the link is not necessary; Weasyl will take the link out of the whole
      embed code.
    </p>

    <figure class="help-image">
      <img src="${resource_path('img/help/help-gdocs-4.png')}" width="540" height="88">
    </figure>
  </div>
</div>
